Note



The definition of Span: The span of a set of vectors is the set of all linear combinations of those vectors. For a set of vectors \{\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2, \dots, \mathbf{v}_n\}, the span is denoted \text{span}\{\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2, \dots, \mathbf{v}_n\}.











Note



Definition of Linear Independence and Dependence: A set of vectors is linearly independent if no vector in the set is a linear combination of the others; otherwise, the set is linearly dependent.








Homogeneous System Form



A homogeneous system has the form A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}





\begin{aligned}
2x + 3y - z &= 0 \\
4x - 2y + 2z &= 0
\end{aligned}

In matrix form: 
\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 3 & -1 \\
4 & -2 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\ y \\ z
\end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
0 \\ 0
\end{bmatrix}











Theorem 9



If a vector space V has a basis \mathcal{B} = \{ \mathbf{b}_1, \dots, \mathbf{b}_n \}, then any set in V containing more than n vectors must be linearly dependent.








Theorem 10



If a vector space V has a basis of n vectors, then every basis of V must consist of exactly n vectors.








Theorem 11



Let H be a subspace of a finite-dimensional vector space V. Any linearly independent set in H can be expanded, if necessary, to a basis for H. Also, H is finite-dimensional and
\dim H \leq \dim V








The Basis Theorem (Theorem 12)



Let V be a p-dimensional vector space, p \geq 1. Any linearly independent set of exactly p elements in V is automatically a basis for V.

Note



Definition: An inner product space is a vector space equipped with an inner product \langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v} \rangle that satisfies: 1. Symmetry: \langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v} \rangle = \overline{\langle \mathbf{v}, \mathbf{u} \rangle} 2. Linearity: \langle a\mathbf{u} + \mathbf{w}, \mathbf{v} \rangle = a\langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v} \rangle + \langle \mathbf{w}, \mathbf{v} \rangle 3. Positive definiteness: \langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{u} \rangle &gt; 0 for \mathbf{u} \neq \mathbf{0}





Norm: \|\mathbf{v}\| = \sqrt{\langle \mathbf{v}, \mathbf{v} \rangle}
Orthogonality: \mathbf{u} \perp \mathbf{v} if \langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v} \rangle = 0
Cauchy-Schwarz: |\langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v} \rangle| \leq \|\mathbf{u}\| \|\mathbf{v}\|




For vectors in \mathbb{R}^n, find the angle between \mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} and \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}.






Solution:






Use the formula: \cos \theta = \frac{\langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v} \rangle}{\|\mathbf{u}\| \|\mathbf{v}\|}
Calculate inner product: \langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v} \rangle = 1(2) + 2(1) = 4
Calculate norms:

\|\mathbf{u}\| = \sqrt{1^2 + 2^2} = \sqrt{5}
\|\mathbf{v}\| = \sqrt{2^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{5}

Therefore: \cos \theta = \frac{4}{\sqrt{5}\sqrt{5}} = \frac{4}{5}
\theta = \arccos(\frac{4}{5}) \approx 36.9°














Note



Definition: The orthogonal complement W^\perp of a subspace W consists of all vectors orthogonal to every vector in W.





If W is a subspace of \mathbb{R}^n, then:

\dim(W) + \dim(W^\perp) = n
(W^\perp)^\perp = W
W \cap W^\perp = \{\mathbf{0}\}





Find the orthogonal complement of W = \text{span}\{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\} in \mathbb{R}^3.






Solution:






Let \mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix} be in W^\perp
Then \langle \mathbf{x}, \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rangle = 0
This gives: x + y = 0
Therefore: W^\perp = \text{span}\{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\}














Note



Definition: The orthogonal projection of \mathbf{v} onto \mathbf{u} is: \text{proj}_\mathbf{u}(\mathbf{v}) = \frac{\langle \mathbf{v}, \mathbf{u} \rangle}{\langle \mathbf{u}, \mathbf{u} \rangle} \mathbf{u}





\text{proj}_\mathbf{u}(\mathbf{v}) is parallel to \mathbf{u}
\mathbf{v} - \text{proj}_\mathbf{u}(\mathbf{v}) is orthogonal to \mathbf{u}
\|\text{proj}_\mathbf{u}(\mathbf{v})\| \leq \|\mathbf{v}\|

